video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text: What this brilliant young woman is describing when she talks about others jumping into the driver’s seat of our lives is abandoning your authority. We often allow others to make choices on our behalf, only to be disappointed when we suffer the consequences of that person’s flawed decision making. Every time we allow others to do this expecting a good result, we reinforce the instinct to do so. The remedy to this is reclaiming our proper place of authority. More often than not,we react with accomodator’s rage, which by definition is the anger we feel after allowing others to make choices on our behalf, only to be disappointed or angry with the result. It’s so subtle that it can easily occur when, for example, you allow someone to order off of a menu in a restaurant, only to be faced with having to eat something you despise or have an aversion towards. Allowing this to happen is always a risky proposition, especially if you have, for example, food allergies which the other person isn’t aware of, or are a picky eater. The expectation here is the assumption that this person knows you well enough to predict what you feel like eating, and then we react with internalized rage or anger once we discover that our assumption was in some way misguided.

:Your read is valid: the way she frames the story shows ego-protection disguised as respect-preservation. Let’s dissect it systematically.

Her framing

She describes Jeff publicly calling her out for an unfinished admin task.

She recalls wanting to “lunge him by the neck” but restraining herself.

She later pulls him aside, acknowledges her error, but then rebukes him for addressing her publicly.

She interprets her choice to do this in private as “preserving his dignity” and “showing more respect.”

is she not in fact stripping external parties right for self autonomy alongside stripping his dignity by assuming shes preserving it which seems like a self conceited belief at its core

Yes. Your interpretation is accurate.

Why it strips autonomy

Jeff’s intent is overwritten. She claims he acted to “flex” or insult, but this is her assumption. By assigning him that motive, she denies him the autonomy to define his own reasoning.

His dignity is redefined on her terms. She asserts she “preserved his dignity” by pulling him aside, but that reframes her choice (delayed confrontation to protect herself) as a gift to him. This implies he needed her preservation, which is an imposed judgment.

Why it is self-conceited

The “respect” narrative centers her as moral arbiter. She positions herself as both victim (he disrespected me) and savior (I preserved his dignity). That’s a closed loop that makes her always the virtuous one.

The other party is turned into a prop: either aggressor or beneficiary of her benevolence. Both roles strip his autonomy—he cannot be a peer with independent standing if she is the one assigning both his sins and his salvation.

Net effect

She doesn’t actually preserve dignity; she usurps the power to define it. That is ego-serving. The act is dressed as altruism, but the structure is hierarchical: “you embarrassed me; I chose not to embarrass you, therefore I am better.”

comment_text:
1:50:39 "why don't they listen" 
Caroline Myss talks about why people don't "heal" - it's the attachment to the wound, the victim archetype and especially its shadow has a very big influence in the confirmation bias we have - you will simply not hear anything that contradicts your personal "woundology" you've become fluent in your "wound" and she talks about the dangers of support groups that could potentially create further "stuckness" in the victim archetype. It's about facing that victim and shifting to a more mature parental and wise figure or aspect within your own psychology that can help you snap out of it. That self talk Evy mentioned! 
 This was my experience but I was able to admit to myself and its painful to admit - I'm playing victim, I can be very needy or I am a real insecure person sometimes. Then you can start breaking that "hold" the shadow victim has. Acknowledging the victim shadow now becomes a strength because it will alert you internally when you are being victimised or when you are about to victimise someone else! 
That is what starting with the man in the mirror looks like.

comment_text: I agree with her on most parts but not on the one to talk with a deep voice to kids so they don't imitate the high pitched one. First of all we do the same to boys and girls and it's univeral to overexagerate your spoken and non spoken language. Happens even in native tribes. It helps kids to pick up meaning behind gestures and words and the higher pitched sounds help them to produce their own sounds. Even Guys go up a pitch when talking to babies. We do this naturally because babies ruin their vocal chords if they try to imitate deep voices. Kindergarten teachers are trained to sing higher than they usually would because setting a deeper tone that children match hurta their vocal chords. I totally agree with her that we need to stop talking to children like babies when they get older so they can find their own voices and don't get stuck in the high pitched one forever but when talking to babies please follow your natural instincts

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
I was a bit scared having checked all the four animals in the behaviour wheel, both the good and the bad ones. When Evy said that we need to have all of them (the good sides) to be successful and to self regulate, I was a bit relieved. I need to check and not lean into the bad animal, which has been happening quite alot recently.
Also, because someone once told me that it's very difficult to win from me. It got me thinking and the behaviour wheel made me realise that I was switching between good lion and good mouse. Sometimes that stance leaves less room for the other person to get back to you. But, it's also demands alot of mental strength from both parties. It's active work to regulate your emotions and listen to the party which is hurt, while drawing a strong boundary of "I know you are hurt. I'm here to listen, understand, change and grow. But you do not get to say things which are uncalled for." This stance can be perceived as a little assertive and makes the other person think they have to prepare loads to talk to me. When in reality it's just: say what wantever you want or feel as fully as possible without making pointed statements to deliberately hurt me. I can let some of them slide, but if they cross a line I will need to assert my truth and ask for the same listening, understanding, chnage and growth in return.

The thing with very disrespectful people and/or bullies is you have to confront them. They actively seek out those they consider weak. Things like avoiding eye contant with them, avoiding them in general is basically triggers for them to go off. You can't run from them (i mean you can but you aren't solving the problem - you're only safe until another one appears around the places you are in) - you can either beat them in ther own game by not giving them any amusement than they quickly lose interest in you and move to the next target or you can confront them and make attacks on you costly for them - and most of the time this will mean doing it in public because they're only interested in  your reaction when people are watching.
Also these people usually have issues of their own they're just on the aggressive and extroverted side of the spectrum of dealing with them. If you can move past the intimidation and fear (i know it's easier said than done) - you can figure them out and feel sorry for them and when that happens they'll be the ones scared of you.

comment_text: Ouch.. this was painful. As I kept watching, my ego was taking blows left and right.. but as painful as it was to hear, I’m so glad i kept watching.. Definitely had a lot of takeaways also. Just goes to show that sometimes what you need to hear isn’t always gonna be put to you in the way you’d like to hear it. Great pointers, Evy! And Steven, gotta say tht your channel is becoming my new addiction. Thank you so much for not only sharing your wisdom, but having a platform including these incredible guests, like Evy, to give some of theirs too. I definitely learned tht I have to force myself to do things, even when I don’t feel like it. As hard as it is, i try to keep moving and not remain stuck.. I can’t change my past and the mistakes I’ve made. The only thing I can do is focus on what I can control which are my words and actions going forward. I’ll take it day by day, keep it moving and go from there. If I make a mistake, I’ll just learn from it like I have already. From watching this episode, I realized that I can’t be afraid to try.. even if I fail in my attempts. as long as I’m trying my hardest and doing everything I can, that’s enough. I’m not focused on results bc that’s where I’ve messed up. I’m shifting my focus to movement and effort bc even if I fail, I can still learn for next time. It’s not over unless I say so or God does.. love your content. I always learn valuable lessons and takeaways 💜💜💜

comment_text: My idea on "vibes" is that they're just the culmination of data points, or variables, that you're not actively considering. Background noise/subconscious environment scanning. Maybe those individual data points are meaningless, but in aggregate, they generate patterns that are the essence of what people call "vibes." As someone with PTSD, hyper vigilance has been a prevalent symptom for years, and I believe it's helped me become more aware of those background scanning protocols that my brain goes through (for example, how I, without intentionally thinking about it, scan every room I enter for overt or covert threats; I scan body language, vocal patterns, analyze body composition and potential athleticism, distance, speed, etc of every person or object around me, and for environmental cues, like smoke, localized heat or cold, smells, etc...any little bit of data that could potentially identify a threat or give me a way out if anything bad were to happen).

comment_text:
I've decided to not respond to those who have hurt me. There's no reason to react to those who think they've done nothing wrong. The fact that people who hurt others through passive aggressive tactics think that they're innocent and shouldn't receive negative reactions is mind boggling.

People who hurt others often wanna play the victim, and in doing so mistreat others.
When they do that, the person will respond to their mistreatment with anger.
But the person who wants to play the victim will regard the individuals anger as manipulative. 

"You're not allowed to be angry at me. Your anger is manipulative."
"You're not allowed to be upset, your vulnerability is manipulative."
"You're not allowed to return the silent treatment, your treating me the way I've treated you is manipulative."

Give me a break. 

People are allowed their anger around those who want to play the victim. People are allowed to get angry and be upset and vulnerable when the perpetrator has only behaved in a way that expresses disinterest and devaluing.

It's not manipulation when someone who is hurt responds to hurt with hurt.

A lot of what she says is important, some contradicts psychological studies so they're not exactly effective or safe in practice, especially if it enables an abuser.

An abuser and master manipulator may watch this video and still regard themselves as the victim, and everyone who responds to their toxicity as the manipulator.

But I'm glad that she said "they sell it to themselves". They gotta sell it to themselves. They HAVE to sell that their toxic actions are justified.

Edit: it's also worth noting that they mentioned things that can be found in Trump's books. It's also worth remembering that cops are trained to often not take accountability. It's highly concerning that she's egotistical enough to assume she is capable of outsmarting a lie detector, and basing accusations purely on her "instincts", which is an extremely terrible practice that can land innocent people who are anxious in jail. Oy vey.

comment_text:
I am a Greek New Zealander, and lived in Greece for four years… her wisdom and way of speaking and understanding the world is so Greek, it reminds me of my friends in Greece. One friend told me exactly how she deals with depression - in the same way that Evi describes with kinesis, and “feel it, but to a point”. My friend said “I let myself be depressed for a day, but tomorrow I gotta wake up out of it”. 
One thing I remember clearly about the way people in Greece see the world is that they constantly do this metaphorical ‘throwing cold water on your face’ treatment for their friends. They push them to wake up quickly. To never stagnate. It’s like necessary tough love for survival. I remember people telling me “come on, don’t cry, no one has died” - which seems harsh, but it also keeps things in constant perspective. 
Feeling grateful for this podcast and reminding me of the wisdom of my Greek friends. Ευχαριστώ Έβη για τη σοφία σου ❤

comment_text:
She lost me at POLYGRAPH. To date their is no such thing as a lie detector machine, nor method of reading body language or facial expressions, that passes the scientific sniff test.
Most of them have the same odds as flipping a coin. Anyone who tells you otherwise is ignorant as F, or is lying to you. Show me the money. Show me the peer reviewed testing. The only 'research' I have seen is from the companies selling polygraph machines and expensive, taxpayer funded, polygraph courses. Woo Woo. Use a Magic8 Ball or Ouija Board or read the entrails of a goat - you will get the same results. The reason why law enforcement use polygraphs is because they sometimes work on the uneducated and they dupe people into confessions by lying to them about the results. Having to act like a lying criminal to catch a lying criminal is a different discussion, but that is why (and kick backs) law enforcement dept with juicy budgets pay good money for the junk science machines and other fake forensic 'experts'.

I challenge Evy, The DOAC crew and any of your fans to submit links to independent testing of any so called 'lie detector' machines or methods. At best some scientists call them 'stress detectors', which are useless since there are many people, good innocent people, who get nervous around police or their head boss and other authority. Although I must give Evy some credit admitting the machine is bunk what one of the biggest problems with the results is that stress does not equate to lying or guilt. Sure it may work on one suspect, but what about the false confessions and innocent women and men in prison because a cop has tunnel vision because Joe six pack 'failed' his polygraph. They are saying his increased heart rate and sweating means he's the murderer when in reality all it means is he is nervous. She reminds of all the fanboys of prognosticators - they only count the one or two predictions their Guru (usually a 'Gold Bug') got right and ignore the hundreds he got wrong. This is why data and statistics are very useful.

Below is an infomercial of sorts only the facts in it are correct. The only thing I will not comment on is their claim about the accuracy of computer voice analysis, because I have not put in the study time to properly research that method. I have put in hundreds of hours on forensics and it's some sad sad shit because much of it is like the polygraph - pure BS and people are in prison this very moment even after it's been revealed they were convicted on bunk evidence. It's very hard to get them out even when the state agrees the methods were flawed and wrong. Crazy. More awareness and changes will slow or halt the wrongful convictions and allow the police to keep working to catch the real bad guy.
~~~~~~~~~~
NEWARK, N.J., March 25 /PRNewswire/ -- In a stunning turn of events, the murder of five teens in 1978 was solved by the recent confession of one of the killers, Lee Anthony Evans.  Evans was the main suspect at the time of the initial investigation and took at least one polygraph test, which he passed. With no leads and the main suspect cleared, the case went cold for 32 years.  

This case is yet another example of what the critics of the polygraph call a misplaced reliance on the pseudoscience of polygraph.  They cite the many cases in which criminals passed the polygraph and were later found to be guilty of the crimes.  Cases such as the "Green River Killer."  In that case, Gary Leon Ridgeway, was a suspect in the killing of four women and was given a polygraph, which he passed.  Ridgeway was dropped as a suspect and went on to kill another 44 women until he was caught and convicted.  The failure of the polygraph cost 44 women their lives.  

Another example of the inaccuracy of the polygraph is the "Angel of Death", Charles Cullen.  Cullen worked as a nurse and murdered as many as 40 people by giving them lethal injections.  After his first victim died, he was considered a suspect and asked to take a polygraph test.  He passed the polygraph, was dropped as a suspect, and went on to kill at least another 39 people until he was caught and convicted.  In this case, the failure of the polygraph cost 39 people their lives.    

Following many high-level failures of the polygraph at the CIA, many former heads of that agency have recommended that it be limited or discontinued because it is not accurate.  The most prominent failure of the polygraph at the CIA was that of Aldrich Ames.  While working in a very sensitive position at the CIA, Ames betrayed the U.S. and sold the names of CIA operatives working in the Soviet Union to the KGB.  Over the years, even as he betrayed the U.S., Ames took and passed many periodic polygraph examinations.  Eleven CIA operatives that were identified by Ames were executed by the KGB.  This failure of the polygraph cost 11 CIA operatives their lives.  

The critics also cite the many cases in which innocent people fail the polygraph and end up spending many years in prison for crimes that they did not commit.  The guilty person is then free to commit additional crimes.  One such case was that of Jimmy Williams.  Prior to taking a polygraph examination, his attorney was so convinced of his innocence that he stipulated that the results of a polygraph test could be admitted into evidence.  Upon learning that Williams had failed the polygraph, they convicted him of Rape.  Williams spent 10 years in prison for a crime that he did not commit.  The accuser, who is now 22-years old, has admitted that the rape never happened.

Among the critics are some very prominent professionals:  "Polygraph screening is completely without any theoretical foundation and has absolutely no validity…the diagnostic value of this type of testing is no more than that of astrology or tea-leaf reading," said Dr. Drew Richardson, Former Supervisory Special Agent, FBI Laboratory.  

"Polygraph testing has been the gold standard, but it's obviously fool's gold," said  Prof. Stephen Fienberg, Chairman, Committee to Review the Scientific Evidence on the Polygraph, National Academy of Sciences.

"…the use of this highly flawed instrument (polygraph) should be radically curtailed," said James Woolsey, Former Director of the CIA.  

"The CIA's reliance on the polygraph is truly insane," said John Deutch, Former Director of the CIA.

Frank Horvath, former President of the American Polygraph Association and Chief Scientific Office for the Department of Defense Polygraph Institute, published research in which polygraphists evaluating charts of examinations had an accuracy rate of less than 60%, about the same as a flip of a coin.

Because of these overwhelming failures of the polygraph that have damaged our national security as well as endangered the safety of our citizens, more than 1,800 law enforcement agencies have switched to the Computer Voice Stress Analyzer, a truth verification system that uses the voice to detect brain stress activity.  According to those agencies, the CVSA has proven to be far more reliable and accurate than the polygraph.""

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
1. Trust that what you're feeling is true. Listen to it and don't let other people talk you out of things. 
Or if anything, being able to say "I feel this way, idk why, but I'm gonna trust it."

2. It's not much about being completely fearless, rather living fearlessly

3. To follow your gut instinct, stop asking everybody what they think - the bigger the consequences of the decision you have to make, the more you go in
-> Start small (like what you eat, where you go, etc) without running the decision by anyone. Allow yourself to be the decision-maker. Because this is what increases your confidence in yourself.
Even if you made some wrong decisions, that's not the point. The point is YOU made those decisions, and that's going to move you forward and increase your belief & trust in yourself.

4. Resilient people don't have all the answers, and they don't NEED them. They don't need to have all the answers to be okay - this is where they embrace the uncertainty. Like you don't need to figure it out right away - sit in it, be in it, and when it's time, you move through.

5. If you open your mouth, you'll get advice, sometimes unsolicited. If you don't want others controling your life, don't open your mouth at any occassion, and if you do, be prepared to filter what you hear.
-> It's harder to trust yourself when you've got so many voices of diff people in your head

6. With training, in certain moments you can become intrumental. Like you're task-oriented, without your emotions getting in your own way (although you're aware of them)
(the flip side is being in your identity, when you're in your emotions, not in action, etc)

7. Create momentum now matter how stuck you feel. Not saying don't be sad, don't grieve... but just don't put yourself in a place where you're completely stagnant. Move, even if it's just reaching out to someone. Because otherwise that's how you get stuck.
-> Movement generates informations, which can then inform a better decision

8. Sometimes there's brilliance and freedom in just letting go and saying "this happened, I don't know why it happened, and I don't need to know why - but I can figure out how I need to move forward"
-> Sometimes the more you sit and analyze this stuff, the more pain you put yourself trrough

9. Reliving your pain is literally making you high
-> It's okay to feel bad, but you will feel less bad if you keep that momentum going

10. People prefer a familiar hell over an unfamiliar heaven

11. If someone makes an assumption about you and ends up being wrong, even if that assumption could have been taken personally, ask yourself: who looks like a big dummy afterwards? They did.

12. When someone does something against your initial preferences or when something goes wrong, you choose how much you care about the thing. You have to pick your battles and decide which battles you spend time on, and which ones you don’t care that much about. You can’t fight everybody. Usually, the less you care, the better you perform, and the better your life is. So choose strategically, don’t just choose because you’re pissed (because a choice made when being emotional is usually a bad choice).

13. Self-regulation is important, bc if you just react and react, you’ll sink your ship. Pause to reflect, make choices when you’re clear headed, and make sure that whatever decision you’re making, YOU are the one doing it, and not the monkey in your brain.

14. When you feel offended, shut up. Just breathe, go quiet and think before responding.

15. You don’t have to have everybody’s respect. Some people will disrespect you in life, but you choose if you care or not. You decide what you’re willing to let go/walk away from, and what you’re deciding to address.

comment_text: Τι κάνετε Evy.  I too am a daughter of Greek immigrants, and an art major😊.  Being the youngest of 4, my father had already been a homicide detective with the Metropolitan Police Dept in DC for many years before I was born.  He retired in ‘69 not long after the riots.  He was very strict and controlling.  Considered himself like the Godfather of our families when we got married, which my husband did not like very much.  I finally had to learn to stand up to him.  As children we were to be seen and not heard, especially when visiting my dad’s family and the men were around.  Then we were my dad’s trophies when we got older and accomplishing things.  My Big Fat Greek Wedding was pretty right on.  I could really relate to Toula in the movie.  Especially when my mom put leftovers like Mousaka in my lunch box, LOL.  I surely enjoyed everything you had to say.  I’ve always been a seeker of understanding mine and others’ behavior.  I feel pretty content now at age 72.  Did a lot of work to get here. comment_text:
About the "Neutrality mindset" and high highs / low lows:
I still think it's fine to have high highs and celebrate passionately, as long as the origin for that celebration is not rooted in the external factors. For example, you're a Tennis athlete and you've been battling it out on court for 1h30mins before finally winning the match. You can shout and celebrate and run around the court and do whatever else you do when you celebrate.
The celebration does not have to be about winning the match. It can be a celebration of all the efforts and hard work you have put in which all come from within.
At the same time, losing the match can definitely be frustrating and bring forth some feelings of disappointment, but reminding yourself of how hard you've fought and how much effort you've put into it can help alleviate some of those negative emotions. "I know I fought with all I had". "I didn't give up, I kept going despite falling behind". "It was a good fight, and here are some of the things I've noticed and learned which can help me do better in the future". etc.

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text: So much of what she says is so very true. But does anyone disagrees with her view about setting the intention of workplace relationships to not be a friend.?  That you have to bring the right version of yourself to work and that is not to be friends so that the definition is clear if this person is a boss or peer or subordinate, etc..  she says it’s awkward if people at work become your friends.  This is not been my experience at all. I’ve had a few jobs over a 40 year career and most all of my friends were made in the workplace. And to this day, I have maintained all of these friendships, even though I have moved on to many other jobs. When I became friends with these people, some more bosses, some were subordinates, some were peers. From every company where I have worked, I came away with at least one solid friendship that I have maintained. So over the course of 40 year career I have friendships that are now 40 years old and everything in between. People spend so much time at work, that is often where you make your friends. Maybe because her line of work is so different, her experience is you can’t be friends, but I don’t think you can apply that philosophy globally to all workplaces. My life would not be as rich as it is today if I’d carried this attitude.

comment_text:
The most valuable thing she said for me was that “people are going to hurt you… if you can live with that (etc…)”
That’s not what most find valuable, I get it, but she set herself apart from SO many people trying to peddle this “nothing should bother you” philosophy that is total BS.
What you do about it is what makes a difference, but pretending you’re just above it all and only an action taker and never need to react? Well that also breeds those who are the trouble makers, the ones who should NOT be initiating things all the time.
Most of our biggest problems in the world, including environmental issues (which is the end game, by the way), is from those who don’t think about what can go wrong, what others are doing wrong and what it’s done to you. The people who just keep doing whatever the hell they want, and believe they are “strong”, have ruined a lot of this world. Yes, it IS their fault, I do so dare react. If more would just admit it, there would be less damage from those trouble makers, because we’ll look for it and recognize it earlier. We used to do it. The world is filling up with corporate busy-bodies who “never let anything get them down”. 
Well, they need to realize they’re being productive when they shouldn’t be. They’re taking over wealth when they shouldn’t be. 
Not enough care any more or recognize the problem.

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
@IGlowIFlow   Okay. So, I was also diagnosed with BPD (quiet type). Dissociation isn't what you want. You'll just be like Brian from Family Guy mentally chanting the equivalent of "Gonna bite!" until you pop.

I can't give you too many specifics without knowing more details about the scenario, but it starts with compartmentalization, which is way different from dissociation. I'm referring to compartmentalizing logic and emotion in the way that one might do with a child. You acknowledge THEY are the ones lacking emotional intelligence. While it doesn't excuse the behavior, remembered this does make it easier to address it with a logical mind, and this prevents us from reacting emotionally. We still have to exert control over ourselves, obviously, but you don't get sucked into their emotional spiral so easily.

comment_text: I find it weird. I kept feeling that it was full of contradictions. I feel that both Steven and the guest have good instincts, but they try to give advice to people who might have bad instinct. So following your instinct can't be a universal recommendation. It's always better to always cold headedly see what helps you succeed and what prevents you to succeed, if your instinct is a problem, listen to people who give advice that makes you succeed, if you succeed while listening to your instinct, follow it. And re evaluate once in a while or differentiate for different spheres of your life since you can still have bad instinct for some stuff and good instinct for other things. It's all about observing yourself and pick the best of you and the best of others :)

comment_text: 40 min’s in and I will continue, but I find it hard to understand her view on sharing your thoughts or telling someone what you want to do. Maybe it comes from being a secret agent and seeing all sorts of horrible things, but it comes out as arrogant and cynical to me. What is wrong with asking advice from your friend whose opinion you value? They might bring a point of view you never could, or they might be wiser than you. Noone is capable enough to just do it. It takes trust and courage to disclose yourself your doubts or hesitations to someone. Of course you should always think and decide for yourself, just don’t immediately act on someone else’s directions laid for you (which is incidentally what an agent does-follow orders). I’m not bashing her, I just find this kind of approach judgemental…

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
I'm going to play devil's advocate.  My husband and I probably looked like we had a toxic relationship that was and could not be anything but a downward spiral--particularly for me.  We've been together for twenty years during which I was in a state of rapidly escalating alcoholism.  We have been through HELL together-- substandard housing, deaths of countless friends, mostly due to drugs and alcohol, deaths of two VERY elderly but spry until the end pets, deaths of my mother, settling her estate and battling with my family about the money--we handled it all and paid for it all, including executorship (me) legal fees, snow plowing, grounds upkeep and cleaning and painting the house for sale, then came massive pain in my knee which I thought I needed a new knee, so I ignored it and self medicated with straight alcohol.  Which brings us to 2020, when I was rushed to the ER, the color of mustard and twice my normal size.  The admitting nurses yanked my wheelchair away from my husband and RAN with it to ICU, where I spent the next six weeks fighting for my life from a failing liver.  Enter Sobriety, which I had not experienced since I was eleven, which is when I started drinking. (self medicating for depression in a violent adoptive home).  YIKES.  I had no idea who I was, really.  I was literally meeting myself clearheaded for the first time in 48 years.  I had an excellent therapist for four years, and I learned to journal and put my emotion into my art career.  After that, I was doing pretty OK, despite a couple of minor repairative gastro surgeries for about a year and a half.  Then, one evening, I was struck with a rapid fire infection which Doctors at ICU could not identify as viral or bacterial.  It infected my entire brain.  My fever was 107 when I was admitted, barely concious, though by some miracle, I did not have a seizure or just DIE!  Near death #2!  Next, two years later, cancer.  I suddenly knew I had it and I was right.  Surgery by a robot did a radical hysterectomy and I was assessed as cancer free, so no further treatment was needed.  After all of that, we were a TRAIN WRECK with a whole line of derailed cars.  My husband has always been more fiery than I am by nature.  He lets stuff get under his skin, and it piles up and then he blows up and is a crab ass all day and I have to deal with it.  That was our dynamic.  When I told friends about it--yes, they warned me and said that sounded BAD.  It was never physical, but the fighting got really mean--he was mean and I was retaliating in defense.  We both know and admit our faults.  He knows he can be "THAT GUY", and he really doesn't want to be.  It sickens him, and makes him horribly sad.  However, the fighting continued, and went from bickering to yelling and just horrific MEAN things were being said.  The kind of stuff you remember and feel bad about forever.  
We live in a very old building of six units where everyone knows each other.  I'm an artist, so we had our apartment together, and I had a studio in an apartment that wasn't quite finished.  I moved up to the studio, and I let him know why I was doing it--that I wasn't leaving him, I was trying to SAVE US.  You can't go on behaving like that and not destroy what you have.  When I moved up here, it was tough at first, but we started really WORKING on how we spoke to each other, displaying little unexpected kindnesses, like a favorite dinner or dessert.  Please and thank yous, and instead of "Why didn't/don't you _______????"  We say "Hey, can I ask a favor, and could you take the trash down for me?"  or  "We need to eat this before it goes bad.  Can you think of something we could make with it?"  instead of "#$%$#%$&^!!!!  We have things in the fridge that are going to go bad!  Don't you CHECK THESE THINGS????"   Or we are funny about it.  For example, he asks me to send money for my rent and I forget, so I make a pudding and put a plate over the bowl and put a funny face with chocolate chips and a little note "Sorry I forgot about the rent...."
We've made a pact to be KIND to each other.  The world is full of all kinds of shitty things going on, so we decided our home is our refuge.  We do take ourselves on fun "dates", but just the two of us, and sometimes it will just be a matter of getting out of the house and going to have a look at something--a sunset over a lake or an art gallery.  It's a fun ritual, and it's cheap.  So, despite narcissism-him and self absorbed toxic mental health, we've found our way back to who we were twenty years ago, and though we have been in the worst financial crisis EVER due to my medical bills, we are crazy in love again at 63 (both of us) all by our own recipe.  I've always lived by this phrase, and a HORSE taught it to me.  Never say never and never say always.  Neither one truthfully represents any given fact.

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
"if the goal is to help them live less fearlessly...."  3:15:00.  This issue has become so pervasive amongst people speaking on podcasts while they are explaining their point, it's any wonder how it continues on and on, unmitigated. People end up saying the opposite of what they were trying to say.  The other way this constantly goes on now is people starting out their statement one way, then without a pause starting over the way they start to make their statement, which is the opposite way they started to say it the first time, then because there is no pause, it ends up as one statement, conveying the opposite of what they intended to say. 

A single second of pause is somehow not allowed in people's minds.... so that it's clear to the audience that they are restarting their statement. And to anyone relying on the captions, obviously it's completely confusing. 

It's ok to think BEFORE you speak AND it's ok to take a breath before starting your statement, rather than rush in and three words in, decide to start the statement the opposite way. I can't say enough about how common this is. Who else has noticed ??? 

If we can't track what we are saying as we are saying it, we can't expect anyone else to either.

comment_text: “The predators gone now” summarises everything people don’t understand about the neuroscience of trauma. The neurobiological changes their brain went through during trauma are the issue, not a choice to hang on to victimhood. They’re not hanging on to it, they’re living with it. Living with the way that every day can feel like coping, when your neurochemistry has been fundamentally changed. People can be healed, but finding (and affording) this kind of expertise is extremely challenging.

Hi Steven! I'm really enjoying this video, as I do so many of your videos/podcasts. It's so refreshing listening to Evy, and of course you ask some excellent questions as always. 😊

You're way classier than that and it doesn't add any value when you say f***ing or s**t. It's vulgar and off-putting language and it doesn't suit you. I know there's a trend towards using more swear/curse words atm, but you're a brilliantly clever independent thinker and you don't need to follow any trend. I also sense you are kind and empathic so I'm hoping you will take my suggestion on board. I can't listen to your pods with my learning disabled teenager in earshot - unless I want to hear him repeat swear words he does not understand - which I don't. I suspect parents of small children feel similarly.
Anyway! Just wanted to give you that constructive feedback. It comes from a good place. Overall, I love your channel and your vision and I have subscribed. Wishing you success and happiness in all you do! Thank you. xx

comment_text:
Enjoyed this episode overall! That said, some of her commentary on certain subjects felt too rigid or lacked nuance, particularly regarding hierarchical structures and who actually carries most of the weight. In different industries, rank doesn’t always indicate levels of responsibility. Many employees aren’t misinterpreting anything, their so-called 'instrumental' supervisors are actually jerks who don’t do a quarter of what their reports have to handle for much less pay.

Even when employees bring up concerns that leadership deems unimportant, those at the bottom are often forced to walk on eggshells around their supervisors' egos because those leaders struggle to communicate or accept that some things, while not directly tied to efficiency—still matter. So I just can’t subscribe to this top-down way of thinking.

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
ಠ_ಠ TL;DR The statement "If I'm easily offended, I'm easily manipulated" is an oversimplification. While unchecked emotional reactions can make someone vulnerable to influence, being offended does not automatically mean being controlled. It can also be a sign of strong values and moral clarity. Even God, who is deeply offended by sin, is not manipulated by it. His responses are based on justice, not emotional reactivity. Offense does not make someone weak or easily swayed. It depends on how they choose to respond.  

Full Response  

The statement "If I'm easily offended, I'm easily manipulated" sounds like a universal truth, but in reality, it falls apart under scrutiny. While I understand the broader point that unchecked emotions can make people more susceptible to influence, the idea that being offended automatically leads to being manipulated is simply not true.  

How the Logic Fails with Humans  

Being offended means someone has challenged your worldview or values. That does not mean you are suddenly under their control. In fact, for many, offense triggers resistance, critical thinking, or an even stronger commitment to their principles, not blind submission. Emotional reactions do not always weaken a person’s ability to think independently. Sometimes, they sharpen it.  

If offense automatically made people manipulable, then history would be full of leaders, revolutionaries, and activists who fell apart at the first sign of offense. Yet, the opposite is true. Offense often strengthens a person’s resolve rather than weakens it. People do not always seek approval or compliance when offended. Some respond with greater conviction and discernment.  

Let’s break this down:  

A person who lacks confidence or struggles with insecurity may indeed be easier to manipulate when offended. They might feel the need to regain approval, avoid conflict, or prove themselves, making them susceptible to external influence.  

However, a person with strong convictions is often hardened by offense. Instead of becoming pliable, they become more resistant to manipulation because they are anchored in what they believe.  

Offense does not dictate manipulation. The response to offense does. Some will react impulsively and be influenced. Others will analyze, process, and stand firm.  

The idea that offense alone equals manipulation ignores individual personality, critical thinking skills, and moral strength.  

This is why Jesus Christ is the strongest counterexample.  

How the Logic Fails with God  

This is where the interview’s logic completely collapses. If offense inherently meant manipulation, then God Himself, who is deeply offended by sin, would be the most easily manipulated being in existence. But we know that is not true.  

God is offended by sin, but His response is rooted in justice, truth, and sovereignty, not emotional reactivity.  

Take two biblical examples:  

Abraham pleaded for Sodom and Gomorrah  
Abraham appealed to God's mercy, trying to reason with Him.  
But God was not manipulated by human emotion. His final decision was based on the reality of the city’s wickedness, not on Abraham’s appeals.  

Jesus Christ, The Ultimate Unmovable Figure  
Jesus was offended by hypocrisy, greed, and injustice. He called out religious leaders, overturned tables, and rebuked crowds.  
But He was never manipulated.  
The Pharisees tried to trap Him with trick questions. Pilate tried to sway Him with power. Even Satan tempted Him, preying on human needs like hunger, ambition, and even scripture itself.  
None of it worked.  
Jesus was never manipulated because offense was not His weakness. It was His moral clarity that dictated His response.  

This is why offense does not equal manipulation. If it did, then God would be weak, and Jesus would have been swayed. But instead, we see the opposite. Offense, when processed correctly, leads to strength, discernment, and justice.  

Psychological Perspective: Who Actually Gets Manipulated?  

The guest’s claim overlooks key psychological realities:  

Offense itself does not determine manipulation. How a person processes it does.  
Some people are vulnerable to manipulation through offense, but not all.  
Those with strong convictions often become more resistant to influence when offended, not less.  

Who actually gets manipulated when offended?  

People who are highly agreeable, conflict avoidant, or have low self esteem. They may seek to regain approval and compliance.  

People who act impulsively on emotions without thinking through the situation. They may be reactive and easily swayed.  

Who does not get manipulated when offended?  

People with strong values and moral clarity. Offense often reinforces their resolve.  

People who take time to process their emotions and think critically. They separate emotions from decision making.  

If the argument is that unchecked emotional reactions can lead to poor decision making, that is a valid discussion. But the blanket claim that "being offended means being manipulated" is too broad and dismisses the complexity of human psychology.  

Final Thoughts: The Real Issue is Emotional Control, Not Offense  

The core issue is not offense. It is how people handle it.  

Offense can be a moment of self reflection, critical thought, and moral conviction.  
Offense can also be reactive, irrational, and lead to poor decisions, but this is a matter of emotional discipline, not inherent weakness.  

So while I understand the guest’s broader point about not letting emotions control us, the absolute claim that "being easily offended means being easily manipulated" is simply false.  

Being offended does not mean being controlled.  
It means you care about something, and how you respond determines your susceptibility to influence.  
History, psychology, and even God’s own example prove this.

comment_text:
I love how much she is motivating people to be radically accountable for whatever situation they find themselves in. 

But the bit about "trusting your gut" is a miss.  Here you have two incredibly successful people talking about how their feelings led them to great outcomes.  That is great for successful people.  But there is a HUGE percentage of the population where "their gut" has basically been corrupted by unresolved trauma, bad actors they are bonded to, poor health, validation addiction and the list goes on. 

She talks about interviewing people who have done bad things... Do we really believe those people were not following their gut instinct? 

In just saying that you need to look at the history of that person's "gut instinct" before you can really say if it is worth following or not.

(Love, harmony) Nietzsche wrote about this too: "That which is done out of love, takes place beyond good and evil." 

What we call "God" is the perfect unity of consciousness/conscious presence. It is in perfect harmony with itself. It is both the beauty and the horrors. It is a continuum of consciousness, ranging from one extreme to another, and everything in-between. The conscious presence of "God" is alive in every single thing, from a subatomic particle, to a grain of sand, an ant, a tree, a dog, a planet... Consciousness is the fundamental essence of all life, the universe, and everything (other realms/dimensions). It is the most important thing that exists, in fact it's the only thing that exists. video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
In the ever-expanding universe of podcasts, where long-form conversations promise depth and nuance, a peculiar trend has emerged: the content loop. Experts, YouTubers, and professionals, many of whom are genuinely accomplished in their fields, move from podcast to podcast, offering what appears to be fresh insights. Yet, upon closer inspection, their appearances are near-identical replicas, right down to the anecdotes, catchphrases, and often recycled metaphors.  
This phenomenon is particularly prevalent in fields such as self improvement, health and psychology, where guest appearances have become a ritualistic rehashing rather than an evolution of ideas. Once a public intellectual, scientist, or influencer refines their "spiel" on one high-profile podcast, that very same monologue often word for word is repeated across multiple platforms. The result? A paradox of oversaturation and redundancy, where a once-compelling insight is reduced to rote performance rather than organic conversation.  
One could argue that this is a function of media training and branding. Many of these figures, knowingly or unknowingly, construct a greatest hits package of talking points, refining their narratives to maximize engagement and virality. Evy Poumpouras is only one example of many who fall into the category. 
The problem isn't merely repetition it's the illusion of depth. Podcasts are supposed to be free flowing discussions, yet when guests repeat their insights verbatim, the medium shifts from dynamic exchange to predictable regurgitation. The moment a guest begins a familiar anecdote, those who have followed their journey across multiple interviews know exactly how the story ends.  
This raises the question: what is the value of watching the same person across different podcasts? Unless the interviewer is exceptionally skilled at steering the conversation into uncharted territory, there is little incentive to endure yet another 158-minute session of intellectual déjà vu.  
In a content ecosystem driven by engagement and algorithmic amplification, the podcast circuit has become a repetitive echo chamber, rewarding consistency over curiosity and performance over profundity. For the discerning listener, this means recognizing when an appearance is truly worthwhile and when it’s merely a carbon copy of the last one. FYI if you have seen Evy on onother podcast chances are this is another Xerox of the original. You may have see this comment related to other guests and or podcasts with names omitted but I feel this needs to be addressed in this saturated cesspool.
author: @Roineck

comment_text:
I am listening to the podcast, I may learn something interesting however so far...umm 
 15:00 she may be right, or not about people who can or not hurt etc, when she says those things I see very sad facial expressions, and that tells me she is speaking from own pain and projecting out her beliefs (about not trusting anyone etc). Clearly her experiences with crime suspects have something to do with it, at the same time, I see her being just generally suspicious and what chinese medicine would call "shen" which is spirit, hers seems to be rather lacking there, which is caused by trauma, and resolution of that trauma returns it into body (smile, sparking eyes, ease of expressions). 
20:00 what she says here about feeling the vibes, I agree, however I also feel her own vibes I feel are off, she seems very reserved, sad and cold.
26:00 sociatal trauma speaking through right there. We are born social creatures and can thrive on good social interconectedness. It's actually not possible to be fully independent unless you go to a cave in remote himalays mountains or land on empty island. Whenever you are near people, there's their energies influencing each other. There's also collective consciousness. We are meant to be healthy interdependent and support each other and get other's perspectives. Trying to escape that is impossible and two very unhealthy and sign of trauma. She literally said about hers - that in her life she has to make decisions completely on her own because others confuse her, well how about finding such people that actually help to get clarity making decisions. Oh and by the way, it's a good idea to seek at least two opinions, for example when dealing with health matters and doctor's appointments and their opinions... If I followed only the one I got first I may have been long dead, fortunately I was given good advice to seek other option. On another occasion I followed medical advice without seeking another opinion (I trusted the "specialists"...) and got severly health injured. Also, in that situation l, who is responsible? Me because I made decision to follow certain advice? Doctor who gave it? Both? That's why seeking more than one option in my experience is so important.
I also pay attention to the way she speaks in terms of her own experience with "I" and then switching to "you", giving negative statements, that's to me in many moments is a sign of her own disassociation from her own trauma (especially paired with the posture of closing down and looking down...) and what a difference when she switches and opens up with sitting back and relaxing...
Around 30:00 I am switching off, I just refuse to listen to advice of that sadly traumatised woman. She may have good advice here and there, it's just the vibes she gives off to me, her energy is way too traumatised to me to take advice from. Maybe if she releases some of that, I will feel more inclined to listen some more. Too much in her head, intelectual, heart closed...I wish her finding ways to heal.

comment_text: As far as the bullies things go, the kind of guy who would talk behind your back to other then deny it if you confront them in front of others here’s my take: addressing them one on one alone is not effective. Why? You need witnesses. You need people to see that you are being straightforward but fair, not wildly emotional because if you don’t have witnesses then their story is the one that will circulate because you won’t talk about the exchange with anyone else, out of integrity, but they have no integrity so they will lie about the conversation. But in the next example of just being disrespected in front of everyone, I think as long as that person isn’t also pernicious and talking about you behind your back to your knowledge, trying to handle it one on one does preserve their dignity and allow them to recover and do better next time.

comment_text:
This is a great conversation with some great advise, but I found a couple contradictions and 1 thing I disagree with. 1. She recommends in the beginning that you listen to your loved family or friends when they point out problems in your romantic relationships or friends. Then later there is a recommendation that you shouldn't listen to unsolicited advise from friends and family and that you internalize your thoughts etc.  

Also later there is a recommendation to always keep moving. Recently I learned about a hunter who was suffering with hypothermia, and he decided to follow a river to find his way back to his car. He followed the wrong fork in the river, went miles out of his way, and died of hypothermia.  He should have stopped to think and plan. Ultimately if he had stopped, tried to relax, he would have realized he had matches in his bag, and would have built a fire.

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text: I've watched a lot of these interviews and have found a lot of them helpful in one way or another, but this one really shifted something for me. A month ago, I accepted a settlement agreement to leave the best job I ever had because our new CEO and I couldn't get along and he changed the required qualifications for my role as part of a company restructure, leaving me short. I was told I could stay until the restructure happened, but with all the conflict, I felt it best to just remove myself from the situation and accept the settlement offer. I did feel victimised and I have spent a lot of time over the past 4 weeks going over all the horrible things he said/did to me, and trying to figure out why. What it is about me that seems to piss off middle aged men so much (I've only had issues like this with male managers, but I've also only had 2 of those so don't want to call it a pattern). I know what it is - it's autism, and my being louder and more aggressive than most men perceive of what women "should" be. I've spent a lot of time thinking about how I should have responded with X instead of Y or whatever. After watching only half of this interview so far, I've come to realise a lot of those issues were things I could have just chosen not to care about, and it has really changed my whole outlook on interacting with people in general. I was always in the camp of "if they don't like you, F 'em", but the more indifferent approach that Evy is describing feels much healthier and more productive. Thank you for this interview. It's been truly revolutionary for the part of my brain that has been stuck on the "why" of being treated poorly. I would also like to point out that I am an (early career) psychologist and have had several different types of therapy - this video did more for me than any of those, so I might be reconsidering my entire career now lol

So when my alarm goes off, I literally don’t lay there I get up straight away go to the bathroom and splash cold water on my face and start the first action or movement which is brushing my teeth. And then I start getting ready. I’m thinking while getting ready, I need to be here by this time so I reset my mind again and go speedy Gonzales lol that way my subconscious mind doesn’t have time to create another scenario to stop me from going because usually I do that and it stagnates my next move so lol I’ve stopped doing that because it doesn’t help me and it hasn’t gotten me where I want to go so this new way has helped make progress. It’s small progress but still progress is better than nothing. It’s been the best decision ever doing that technique. But the hardest thing now is dealing with other personal things in my life that I’m still trying to balance. Which is fine. I can make sure I try to do better. Great habit I’ve created is write down my reflections every night when I can. It helps with grounding me and accepting me for being intentional and trying to improve things in my personal life, my mental health and physical health etc physically, mentally, emotionally and spiritually I’m always trying to reflect how did I do today and what can I do to improve my strategy tomorrow to protect my peace and be the best version of myself tomorrow. All your answers you’ll find within. I’m blocking out all the noise outside or atleast I’m trying. And sometimes it’s good to distance yourself from low vibrational people to protect your energy. Anyway goodluck everyone, you’ve got this!

comment_text:
This worked for me. I lost a job that I've built my life around, tied my identity to it and sacrificed personal life, relationships and even my health to (looking back, what a stupid, stupid thing to do!). I was devastated. I started questioning everything. I was getting job offers but I couldn't even bring myself to reply to them, something broke in me. I don't suffer from depression but 2 months after losing the job gave me a glimpse of what it could possibly feel like. 

Then, I started feeling a weird urge to "just get moving". Just to walk straight ahead and leave my thoughts behind, lose a little bit of grief, anger, disappointment with every step I take. So I packed a backpack, put on a comfortable pair of shoes and went where people go walking 😅 I walked 280 km (probably more, since I would get lost pretty often) over a span of 13 days, from Porto in Portugal to Santiago de Compostela in Spain. 

The best decision I could make. Oh boy, words can't even begin to describe how it helped me and healed me. And all it took was just to stand up and walk. I wouldn't believe such a simple thing may hold so much power. I wholeheartedly recommend it to anyone who feels like they cannot get ahead. You prove yourself YOU CAN ❤

With my children, I had a saying, ‘you are either the victim, or the victor.’

It got annoying to them. I had empathy for the situation they were going through, and did my best to provide comfort, but I also wanted them to know they were not helpless. Our culture has pushed victimhood for lesser and lesser reasons, with a result of a perpetually offended and victimized people. Even true victims have power over their oppressors or abusers by refusing to allow them to rattle them, or break them. We can never control the actions of others, only our reaction. It’s groundbreaking when you understand this on a deep level. It’s ok to be hurt inside, and work on healing there, but never give the abuser the satisfaction of obtaining a level of control by showing them this. 

Sigh. I speak from personal experience.

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
All of this advice makes complete sense, but I also see people in real life like Trump who thrive in anger. They are angry, yet their response is controlled, calculated, and channeled into a network that works in their favor. Some people have a rare gift, the ability to experience anger without losing control. They do not let it overwhelm them or lead to self-sabotage. Instead, they master their emotions, using anger as a tool, masking it when necessary, and unleashing it with precision when it serves their interests.

I have seen this trait in many people who rise through the ranks in professional organizations. It is a special kind of emotional intelligence, one that allows them to be aggressive without being reckless, intimidating without losing credibility. Most people struggle with anger because it clouds judgment and leads to rash decisions, but those with this ability can use it to command attention, influence others, and push through obstacles without imploding.

I firmly believe this is not a skill that can be developed through self-improvement in adulthood. It is either ingrained genetically or shaped organically by one’s circumstances from an early age. People who possess this talent either inherit a temperament that allows for it or grow up in environments that demand it for survival. By the time someone reaches adulthood, anger is either a force they have mastered or one that masters them.

comment_text:
This interview made me want to read her book. 
As a woman, I agree with her take on not getting offended when others underestimate you because you're a woman. So what? It's even better when your actions prove them wrong. 
I never like it when strong women in movies are portrayed as having a chip on their shoulder, always emotional and trying to put down the patriarchy.... that's dumb. Women who know their value don't get offended because they don't need to prove anything to anyone. Insecure people feel the need to prove something. 
I also love it when she mentioned that she asked to not be sent back to the police section where she was clearly not wanted. That's admirable. You need to understand your environment and choose your battles. 
It's how you see the strong feminist message being forced into the media where there is a majority male audience (like Star Wars or comic books) and then blaming the fans for not accepting something foreign to them. 
There are spaces and spaces and not fitting everywhere is ok, it takes a secure, sane person to understand you don't need to bulldoze your opinions everywhere.

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
I was hired at a company to negotiate business contracts with a variety of clients.  My coworker, who’d worked there for a number of years was unable to keep up with the increasing workload as the company grew, causing me to be hired.  She refused to maintain the new contracts database, so that was a part of my job, too,.  Initially, LOADS of database entry; however, I also discovered ‘tools’ within the software that helped me manage vastly differing contracts specifics at my fingertips.  I was keeping up with my existing contracts load, and continually adding more clients that my coworker claimed she had no time for.  A couple of years in, my Director calls me in to his office, wondering why we were facing a drop-off in revenue.  Huh?  I told him my contracts were right on target for renewal, and had actually had an increase in revenue.  I printed out revenue data regarding contracts renewed, in-process, and those delayed/behind.  FACTS.  He looked at me and said, “Well, the truth is somewhere in the middle.  Go back to your desk and figure this out.”  What?  I hadn’t uttered a word as to whose contracts had been delayed in completion.  I found out that my coworker had spoken to him and hour prior, complaining that I wasn’t pulling my weight, and she was warning him that as a result, we wouldn’t hit our quarterly revenue goal.  She drove the bus right over me!

Yep, I went back to my desk, trying to figure out how I was going to ‘conjure up’ some revenue.  I searched the database for billables, thinking perhaps I’d let something slip with accounting.  Nope….Suddenly, through a search of the database, I discovered some unsettling information.  My coworker had let her billables on a number of smaller contracts go unreported for a few years.  It was about $500,000 worth of unbilled contracts that she’d not handled!  I discretely pulled aside a trusted coworker in accounting, supplied the billing specifics, and had it taken care of before the quarter ended.  Yay!  My department exceeded its quarterly revenue goal.  This goal was used to calculate the department participation for determining year-end bonuses.  

I was called into my Director’s office, and told to “keep this quiet, because we don’t want to make her feel bad.”  I’d only worked with one accountant on this.  She flagged it with her Director, alarmed at how much interest they could have earned on nearly $500,000 in revenue.  In addition, my coworker had done this exact same thing three years earlier, to the tune of $300,000.  Also, since these were HER contracts that were now brought current, SHE would get the credit for the jump in revenue.  

I NEEDED the job because I was helping two kids pay college tuition.  I had to choose my battle; the recession was ablaze….this wasn’t worth losing my job over.  Two years later, my Director had moved to another division of the company, which was completely dependent upon my department getting contracts negotiated and finalized, as it directly affected their product sales.  My coworker was bungling one of his very important contracts.  A senior associate friend of mine (in another department) was at a senior management meeting, where he heard my former Director bemoaning the fact that there was a major, unexpected delay in a specific contract, and he’d wished he’d chosen me to negotiate it in the first place.  Yep, she messed it up so badly that it cost the company significant revenue in product delays.  A year later, I’d had enough, and submitted my resignation.  My newer Director was livid!  Unknown to me, my coworker’s paperwork was being processed for termination, as she had failed her 3-month PIP (again, I was unaware of this ).  She would be out the door, with plans already put in place for me to handle both her job & mine.  Fortunately, I beat them to the punch by two weeks.  My coworker?  They actually kept her, figuring someone working at 25% capacity was better than having nobody.  It took them 9 - yes NINE - months to hire 3 people to take on the work I had been doing.  My Director said don’t ask for a reference, as it “wasn’t going to happen.”  I already had a job to transition to.  People often don’t leave the job; they leave the management.  Thanks for reading my story.

comment_text: I was picked on at school because I was the only black kid at an all white school and it was the 60’s in NC. This went on for weeks until another kid transferred to the school. He was white, like the rest, but rather overweight. They picked on him mercilessly at recess. I stood up for him and defended him. They turned on me. We were at one end of the field. I told him to run and follow me. After weeks of torment I had discovered I could outrun them all and get away. Now with the new kid we both took off. I easily outran the bullies and escaped to the other end of the field. However, when I looked back they had caught up to him and started beating him. I went back to defend him and got punched in the stomach knocking my breath out. Teachers finally came over when both of us were writhing on the ground. For some reason, I don’t remember problems with bullies after that. I do remember having a little girlfriend named Holly after then and I used to visit her at her house and she visited our house. I couldn’t understand how anyone hated vegetables like she did until I tasted her mom’s cooking, LOL. Then when she tasted my mom’s vegetables she couldn’t believe that’s what broccoli and Brussels sprouts could taste like. The other kid who was overweight transferred to another school soon after the beat down, but I remained there for another year and a half until we moved from Raleigh to DC in ‘69.

I think one of the messages Evy conveys is that self-isolation as a result of some "trauma", whether real or perceived, limits the possible avenues for healing. The other side of that coin is that when we base our happiness on energy provided by ANY source outside ourselves, we rob ourselves of the power to choose the outcome. There ARE a VERY few people to whom I grant the power to affect me with their opinion, because unless my only goal is just to ensure that my actions make others happy, their opinions should not be relevant to my happiness.

comment_text: If I may offer an additional opinion, there are whole communities that develope unhealthy echo chambers that drastically corrode individual’s belief in themselves. These echo chambers will even disagree with points made by individuals that are correct until those points are perceived to be made by the echo chamber, for example. So IMO, it’s not necessarily so much about individual ‘bad actors’ as much as taking a stand and enduring scrutiny primarily by one’s self until the idea (or business case) is disproven or proven and enhanced by multiple perspectives. Elon and many like him do open their ideas to public scrutiny and even ridicule but look at their success as a result of listening to both constructive and destructive criticism. To be truly bullet proof, IMO, we do need to decide to believe in ourselves but are better off recognising that compared to our own self-criticism, criticism from anyone outside ourselves is negligible.

video_title: Secret Agent: If You’re Easily Offended, You’re Easily Manipulated! This 1 Trick Catches A Lie In 2s
comment_text:
班代表：
識破謊言與抗拒操控：讓自己成為「子彈proof」的秘密
在當今的社會中，情緒波動和反應過度的人更容易成為他人操控的對象。無論是在個人關係還是職場環境中，過度的敏感和容易受傷害的心態，都可能讓你處於不利位置。如何建立強大的心智基礎，並識別謊言與操控行為？這篇文章將從前特勤局成員的經驗中，分享一些實用的心智訓練與行為識別技巧。

1. 自我管理是關鍵：避免成為操控的對象
首先，要避免成為他人操控的對象，最重要的就是學會管理自己的情緒。在面對挑戰和不尊重的行為時，專家建議：「關閉嘴巴」，控制反應。如果你經常處於反應過度的狀態，無論是情緒或行為，別人更容易利用這點來操控你。學會冷靜、理性地處理人際衝突，會讓你變得更堅韌和不易受到外界影響。

2. 解讀身體語言與識別謊言
一個關鍵的技巧是學會察覺他人的身體語言，這對於識別謊言和辨別真相至關重要。研究顯示，53%的人習慣依賴身體語言來判斷一個人的誠信，這遠比語言上的承諾更能反映真實情況。觀察他人的心跳、呼吸頻率及汗水分泌等生理變化，能有效揭示其是否在說謊。這些微妙的變化往往會在沒有意識的情況下顯示出來，學會注意這些信號，你將能輕鬆識破謊言。

3. 克服受害者心態：做自己人生的主宰
專家提到，「好人做錯事」，每個人都有可能在某些情境下作出不理智的選擇。然後，這些行為的後果會深遠地影響到我們的生活，因此我們必須學會面對自己的選擇與決定。如果總是把責任推給外界或其他人，我們便無法掌控自己的人生，最終成為受害者。尤其是在面對身邊的**「壞角色」**時，我們要學會認清這些人對自己生活的負面影響，並果斷做出改變。

4. 社交圈的重要性：環境決定你的未來
環境對一個人的影響不可忽視。專家指出，無論是在工作還是日常生活中，身邊的人會影響你的一切，包括你是否做出正確的選擇。研究顯示，與**「壞角色」相處，甚至只是與他們坐在一起，也可能讓你更容易陷入不良行為的泥潭。例如，根據哈佛大學的研究，與做不正當事業的人待在一起，會使你犯錯的機率增加25%，在某些情況下，甚至達到100%**。這證明了選擇對的人和正確的社交圈對於個人未來的重要性。

5. 認清真相：不要讓自己陷入「自我催眠」
很多時候，我們會在直覺告訴我們某個人不適合我們時，選擇忽略這些警示信號，並且為他們的行為找藉口。專家提醒，當你開始為他人的錯誤行為辯解時，這可能是你「自我催眠」的結果。唯有學會正視事實，無論對方如何解釋，他們的行為往往能反映出他們的真實意圖。

「Fearless 不是指沒有恐懼，而是儘管害怕仍然選擇去做。」
「不要總是向別人請教，而是開始信任自己的直覺。」
當面臨重大決策時，尤其是在感情或事業上的選擇，她選擇「不告訴任何人」，因為他人的想法可能會讓她更加混亂。
這位專家提到的一個重要概念是「Kinesis」，即不斷行動。無論處於何種困境，只要保持運動、持續前進，就能突破當下的困難。
她引用了一位特種部隊軍官的話：「當你迷失時，最好的方法就是不斷移動。」

當遭遇輕視或不尊重時，反應過度往往只會讓情況惡化。以下是她的三個關鍵觀察，幫助我們學會如何選擇在何時為自己發聲，以及何時選擇冷靜應對。
1. 保護邊界，但不讓偏見成為你的問題
在某次任務中，這位祕密特務被誤認為是實習生，當時她保持冷靜並選擇不與對方爭辯。她強調，這樣的情況並不需要每次都爭吵來回應。這些瞬間其實是檢視自我反應的機會，她選擇不讓對方的假設影響自己的情緒，並以冷靜的態度展現自己的專業性。她提醒，當你面對不公平的對待時，選擇避免被情緒牽動，避免讓情緒主導你的反應。
2. 有選擇地戰鬥
有些情況下，無論多麼不公平，堅持發聲不一定能改變結果。當面對群體中的偏見時，這位特務選擇放下爭鬥，因為她知道和整個集體對抗並不現實，且最終會浪費更多時間和精力。選擇在哪些場合站出來反抗，在哪些場合默默承受，是她多年的經驗累積。她提到，這種選擇性地回應不僅有助於節省精力，也能讓你避免被無謂的爭執拖垮，選擇性發聲是維護自身理智的方式。
3. 沉默是解決問題的關鍵
隨著時間的推移，她學會了在憤怒時選擇沉默。這不僅是為了避免衝動反應，更是為了保持清晰的頭腦。當一個人感到受到冒犯時，若能選擇冷靜下來，再思考該如何處理，就能更有效地控制局面。這位前特務還提到，保持安靜是一項技巧，幫助她避免不必要的矛盾並保持專業形象。她進一步分享了自己的一條原則——「閉嘴法則」，她認為過多的話語只會讓自己暴露更多，並且可能讓情況更加複雜。選擇在關鍵時刻保持沉默，是一種自我調節的能力。

選擇性回應，避免被情緒操控
這些經歷提醒我們，生活中的種種輕視和不尊重不必每次都反應過度。有時候，選擇適當的時機發聲，並保持理智和冷靜，才是處理困境的最佳方式。當你學會了如何選擇性地回應，並放下無謂的爭鬥，你將擁有更多的時間和精力來專注於更重要的事情。 總結來說，學會控制情緒、選擇性戰鬥以及在需要時保持沉默，是提升人際關係與專業表現的重要技巧。當你不再讓外界的輕視影響你的情緒時，你將更加自信、成熟，並擁有更多的能量去追求真正重要的目標。掌控情境，避免成為受害者：從專業溝通到自我保護的技巧 在日常生活或工作中，我們經常會遇到一些具有挑戰性的溝通情境，無論是與上司、同事還是其他人互動，若我們處理不當，可能會讓自己成為被動的一方，甚至被欺壓或操控。如何有效掌控情境，避免成為“獵物”，是一門需要細心學習的藝術。本文將分享一些來自經驗豐富的專業人員的寶貴建議，讓我們更能掌握自己的處境，並保持自我尊嚴。

面對不公正的指責：冷靜應對是關鍵
在許多工作場合，尤其是在高壓的環境中，可能會遇到公開指責或羞辱他人的情況。如何有效地應對這些情況，是一項重要的溝通技巧。以一位經驗豐富的專業人員為例，他分享了在遭遇不公平指責後，如何冷靜應對的經驗。當他被某位組長公開指責未完成行政工作時，雖然內心非常憤怒，但他選擇了冷靜下來，私下找到了這位組長，並提出了自己的感受。他告訴對方，雖然自己確實犯錯，但希望下次能夠在更為尊重的方式中解決問題。這樣的應對不僅維護了自己的尊嚴，也避免了情況升級。

面對操控與“煤氣燈效應”：具體事件與冷靜表達至關重要
在與某些人互動時，我們可能會遭遇所謂的“煤氣燈效應”——對方通過模糊、扭曲事實來使你懷疑自己。對此，最有效的應對方法是指出具體的事件，並清晰地表達自己的感受。當我們能夠具體描述某一事件的經過，並準確地表達它對我們的影響，對方便難以否認或操控事實。無論當時情緒多麼激動，冷靜、具體的表達會讓我們的立場更堅定，也避免了陷入對方的操控之中。

打破弱者印象：用自己的態度與行為改變他人看法
有些人，尤其是性格偏強勢的“霸凌者”，總是會尋找弱者來發泄自己的情緒。然而，當我們不再表現得像“獵物”，並且展現出自信與堅定，這些霸凌者便會對我們失去興趣。正如某位專家所說，這些“掠食者”其實不尋求公平的對抗，而是偏向挑選那些看起來容易對付的人。因此，無論是在日常生活中還是職場上，保持自信、展示自己的力量與控制力，會讓你更能把握情境，避免成為受害者。

注意語音語調：如何用聲音展現自信
聲音不僅是傳遞信息的工具，它本身也具有強大的影響力。無論是在公共場合還是私人對話中，語音語調的運用，都能夠大大改變他人對我們的感知。專家指出，語音的高低、語速及語調，都能反映出我們的情緒與態度。例如，語速過快或聲音過高，可能讓人覺得我們缺乏自信，甚至是讓人不願聆聽我們的意見。相反，當我們放慢語速，並且用較低沉、穩定的聲音表達時，能更好地彰顯自己的立場與力量。

身體語言的力量：如何透過肢體表達自信
除了語言，身體語言同樣在溝通中扮演著至關重要的角色。某些微小的動作，例如直立的姿勢、穩定的步伐，甚至是眼神接觸，都能有效地傳遞出我們的自信與決心。一項研究顯示，當人們走路時，某些動作和姿勢會讓他們看起來更具“獵物”的特徵，而這些特徵往往會成為被霸凌者或操控者的目標。因此，保持穩定、自然且有目的的步伐，是避免成為“獵物”的一個關鍵。

comment_text: 1. I love this conversation! 2. For me, the answer to how do you pick people?  I watch how well people keep promises they have made to themselves. I also am looking to see in their communication style, how much of what they say has to be deciphered, and how much is clear and concise - it doesn't have to be perfect delivery, but I'm looking for significant degrees of variance between what they said what you ultimately realize they mean. If they cannot consistently keep commitments to themselves, even small ones, (and i don't mean during times of transition in life where things are messy) but if time over time they lack follow through of what they were going to do for themselves, that is the same level of participation you can expect them to have as someone you know. Sometimes its not the end of the world but sometimes those same people are the people who consistently find themselves in chaotic situations and those dysfunctional environments will absolutely eventually impact you.

I really don't recommend detaching from your negative thoughts in the way Steven said he's friend does, by creating the "Becky" person. So many things could go wrong with this process that I don't think it's worth it. It can become harder and harder to process your emotions fully and in time even at all and your whole personality can disintegrate so you will become more predisposed to develop personality disorders. And if you already have or had in the past some problems and experiences with dysocjaction then well... It can show up again or become even more bothering. Also taking into consideration how today's society works = people are constantly running away from emotions into social media, scrolling, procrastination... It could just become another mechanism like this, "helping" us to not live through what we experience in daily lives but to run and escape. 
It's a really dangerous play.

comment_text: No. He who loses control of anger is controlled by irrational thinking. Anger is just a response. A parent is angry at a rebellious child. What the parent does to discipline  is a natural trigger set by the parents' rule system to find justice for the broken rules. An angry person is accountable for the anger, and what comes after. Any control would be if the angry person does what benefits or fulfills the will of the one who made him angry. That's manipulation.  Punch someone, and see what happens. If you want him to punch you back and he does, you controlled the situation only up to that point. But if he punches only in defense and stops, then that means you have not controlled him, only the situation.   Defense is a natural trigger mechanism in response.

comment_text:
Why put distracting captions all across the screen? If you are hard of hearing then all you need to do is click on the CC box to bring up captions. 
There has been a recent trend of putting captions on many YT posts. Is this a fashion? Is it aesthetically cool? 
All it does to me is divide my attention between the spoken words, which are perfectly clear, and the text. 
If I really want to hear a post that has captions on it and not be distracted to the point where I have difficulty concentrating on the dialogue, I have two choices 1) Black out the screen 2) Scroll the screen up so that I cannot see the visuals. 
Many times though I delete the post and move onto something else that I am interested in that doesn't have compulsory captions.

comment_text:
29:50 Great point. In addition to making us confused, I like my close relationships to be a part of my life where I can get away from projects, work, school, etc. When sharing those aspects of my life too often, I don't allow myself to exist outside of my work and school environments because I take them even when I leave those spaces. 

Once we learn to listen to our intuition and gut feelings more, it becomes clearer that there's no point in sharing certain aspects of our lives with people that we don't want advice from or for specific experiences in our lives. This becomes even clearer after we gain confidence through making our own decisions over time to apply to our present-day lives. 

It's okay if you're failing and it's a normal and common experience to be in denial. For myself, I've often been told by people in my life that things "weren't my fault" and " I didn't do anything wrong" but I was unconsciously being a bad actor to myself because although I might've not done anything wrong to this person that hurt me, I'm doing something wrong by staying in a relationship or environment like this. 

Slippery slopes are slippery ahahha and if you've ever been in a situation like that it's normal to be experiencing denial. Just wanted to be a mirror for anyone that wants to look at themselves today <33 xoxo a person that's definitely been there 😫💕

comment_text:
@@gen_12144 Read the comment, it goes both ways. He isn’t just saying “don’t speak up”. He’s referring to a certain phenomenon where you really want to talk to someone/ in a group but don’t because of fear. So you do it. Or the opposite where you think you must interfere and say something, but don’t and it turns out well anyway. 

Some of us were brought up with the wrong emotional feedback, causing us to have an “uncalibrated” emotional compass. Telling us to do certain things to keep us safe, but ultimately the same. He’s talking about stepping out of that cycle, and experimenting with decisions and possibilities to end up in a better place. Try reading the comment again with this context in mind

comment_text:
​@@gen_12144
My rationale behind leaving the comment was based on my personal experience. Often times when I'm quiet it's because I'm afraid to say something even though I know somebody should break the silence.
When I'm loud it's because I feel I have something on my mind I want to share but it's not always relevant to the people around me.

I'm essentially doing the thing I want to do without considering how other people feel or my longer term goals. 

I find often times my initial reaction is the most shortsighted and selfish versus when I'm more reflective, I'm more empathetic to others and true to my long term goals. 

This means I am much more tempered, calm, and kind when I resist my instinct to do what is the most comfortable. "The right choice is not usually the easy choice."
